"title": "7565: Sanhedrin",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7565",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>The Hebrew form of the Greek word “synedrion”, a council. The high court of the Jews, presided over by the high priest. Its 71 members included chief priests, elders and teachers of the law.</p>\n<h2>Jesus Christ and the Sanhedrin</h2>\n<h3>Herod called together the Sanhedrin on hearing of the birth of Jesus Christ</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt2:4\">MAT 2:4</a></strong> <em>This is probably a reference to the entire Sanhedrin.</em></p>\n<h3>Jesus Christ acknowledged the authority of the Sanhedrin</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt5:22\">MAT 5:22</a></strong></p>\n<h3>Jesus Christ foretold that he would suffer at the hands of the Sanhedrin</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt16:21\">MAT 16:21</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark8:31\">MRK 8:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke9:22\">LUK 9:22</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt20:18\">MAT 20:18</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark10:33\">MRK 10:33</a></p>\n<h3>These prophecies were fulfilled</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:57-Matt26:68\">MAT 26:57–26:68</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:58-Mark14:65\">MRK 14:58–14:65</a></p>\n<h3>The Sanhedrin plotted to kill Jesus Christ after he had raised Lazarus</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John11:47-John11:53\">JHN 11:47–11:53</a></strong></p>\n<h3>The Sanhedrin, powerless to execute anyone, brought Jesus Christ to Pilate</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John18:28-John18:31\">JHN 18:28–18:31</a></strong></p>\n<h2>Nicodemus and Joseph of Arimathea were members of the Sanhedrin</h2>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/John3:1\">JHN 3:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark15:43\">MRK 15:43</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:50-Luke23:52\">LUK 23:50–23:52</a></p>\n<h2>The term Sanhedrin could also apply to local councils</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt10:17\">MAT 10:17</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark13:9\">MRK 13:9</a></p>\n<h2>Peter and John were brought before the Sanhedrin</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts4:5-Acts4:21\">ACT 4:5–4:21</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:21\">ACT 5:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:27\">ACT 5:27</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:34\">ACT 5:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts5:41\">ACT 5:41</a></p>\n<h2>Stephen appeared before the Sanhedrin</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:12\">ACT 6:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts6:15\">ACT 6:15</a></p>\n<h3>Stephen angered the Sanhedrin by his defence</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:54\">ACT 7:54</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:57-Acts7:58\">ACT 7:57–7:58</a></p>\n<h2>Paul and the Sanhedrin</h2>\n<h3>Paul was commissioned by the chief priests to persecute the church</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:14\">ACT 9:14</a></strong> <em><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:5\">Ac 22:5</a>  makes it clear that the entire Sanhedrin was involved.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:1-Acts9:2\">ACT 9:1–9:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts9:21\">ACT 9:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts26:10-Acts26:12\">ACT 26:10–26:12</a></p>\n<h3>Paul was brought before the Sanhedrin</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts22:30-Acts23:1\">ACT 22:30–23:1</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:6\">ACT 23:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:28\">ACT 23:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts24:20\">ACT 24:20</a></p>\n<h3>Conspirators plotted to bring Paul before the Sanhedrin again, but he escaped</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:12-Acts23:15\">ACT 23:12–23:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts23:20\">ACT 23:20</a></p>\n<h3>The Sanhedrin brought Paul to the Roman governor, Festus</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts25:1-Acts25:2\">ACT 25:1–25:2</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts25:15\">ACT 25:15</a></p>",
